720983f-a.text:
lLexington Avenue, north from East 42nd Street, showing
prominently the westerly sida of the arterial thoroughfare.
At the loft is the Hotel Commodore. Above samo is the lot
where the Graybar Building (420 Lexington Avenue) will be
erected. Next in order are,the American Express Co. office
building and the old and new units of the Grand Central
Palace buildings. The Hotel Barclay is beyond the latter.
To the right is the five story structure that was demol-
ished in 1928 for a site for the present Chrysler Building.
December, 1925
Brown Bros.

730400f-b.title: General view - [Manhattan - Lexington Avenue - 42nd Street (East) - Chanin Building.]
730400f-b.text:
A general view northward from atop the Chanin Bldg., located
at the S. W . corner of Lexington Avenue and E. 42nd Street, showing
a panoramic arrangement of the Grand Central 2one and the area to
the north. View 1 shows the midtown section between Sixth Avenue
(left) and Lexington Avenue (right). This contains the 70 story
R.C.A. Bldg., the Grand Central Bldg., the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel,
and the Teneral Electric Bldg. In the center background is Central
Park. View 2 shows the East Side- Yorkville fringe of Manhattan.
Here are numerous apartment houses, hotela, tenements and lofts.
These are framed by the G.. Bldg on the left and the Chrysler on
right. The white pile in the center background near the East River
is The New York Hospital and Cornell University Medical College.
This is to the north of the queensboro Bridge and opposite Welfare
Island. The latter lies in the center of the East Eiver and was
formerly known as Blackwells Island. Beyond this appears the
Astoria section of Aueens, the Triboro and the Hellgate dridges,
and the distant outline of the Bronx.

730401f-b.title: General view - [Manhattan - Lexington Avenue - 42nd Street (East) - Chanin Building.]
730401f-b.text:
A general view eastward towards the East niver from the Chanin
Building at the S.o. corner of Lexington Avenue and E. 42nd Street,
showing in a set of three views, a panoramic arrangement.
View 1 emphasizes the midtown East Side area with its New York
Hospital-Cornell University Medical College Center; No. 2, the
publishing zone at 43rd, 44th and 45th Streets; and No. 3, Tudor City
and the Edison electric plant. In the background, across the River, is
the Long Island City sector of the Borough of Queens. Note the Queens-
boro Bridge extending towards same across the river and Welfare Island.
The buildings partly shown at the various margins are the Chrysler and
the News.
October 3, 1936
Views 1,2 and 3
P. L. Sperr
NO REPRODUCTIOS
